Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-24

Title   : Global South should use existing forums to enhance solidarity: Jaishankar
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-24T15:06:41
Fetched : 2025-09-24T17:21:38.232584
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/global-south-should-use-existing-forum-to-enhance-solidarity-jaishankar/article70089720.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
External Affairs Minister S Jaishankar has said the Global South should use existing forums to strengthen consultations to enhance solidarity and encourage collaboration as they navigate challenges of the increasingly uncertain times.
Developing countries must work to build resilient, reliable and shorter supply chains that would reduce dependence on any single supplier or any single market, Jaishankar suggested in his speech at a high-level meeting of Like-Minded Global South Countries on the sidelines of the 80th session of the United Nations General Assembly in New York on Tuesday.
The challenges for the Global South identified by the Minister, include volatility in trade, uncertainty in investment flows and interest rates, the “catastrophic” slowing down of the Sustainable Development Goal (SDG) agenda, shocks of the Covid pandemic, two major conflicts in Ukraine and Gaza and extreme climate events.
“Most of all, the rights and expectations of developing countries in the international system – which has been so assiduously developed over many many decades – are today under challenge,” he said.
Jaishankar proposed some points for collective consideration of developing countries. These include utilising existing forums to strengthen consultations among Global South with a view to enhance solidarity and encourage collaboration.
Specific strengths
He suggested that developing countries should bring to the table specific strengths, experiences and achievements that may have been individually developed but which can benefit all.
“Some good examples of these are vaccine production, digital capabilities, education capacities, agro-practices and SME culture,” he said.
Jaishankar said in areas like climate action and climate justice, developing countries should come up with initiatives that serve the Global South rather than justify the Global North.
He also suggested that countries should discuss the promise of technologies on the horizon, especially AI, and work towards reforming the United Nations and multilateralism as a whole.
Published on September 24, 2025

Title   : HSBC Global expects Sensex to hit 96k by next year-end
Source  : www.thehindubusinessline.com
Published: 2025-09-24T13:54:20
Fetched : 2025-09-24T17:21:38.232584
URL     : https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/markets/hsbc-global-expects-sensex-to-hit-96k-by-next-year-end/article70088839.ece
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Notwithstanding geopolitical turbulence and trade tariff war, HSBC Global Investment Research expects bellwether Senex to hit 96,000 points by the end of next year on the back of government-initiated reforms playing out.
Though foreign funds have withdrawn significant amounts from India in the last 12 months, a period in which the market has seriously underperformed, local investors have remained resilient, said the report.
While earnings growth expectations can fall a little further, valuations are no longer a concern, government policy is becoming a positive factor for equities and most foreign funds are lightly positioned, it said.
“We think Indian equities now look attractive on a regional basis and upgrade the market to overweight (from neutral). As in China, US tariffs will have little impact on the profits of most listed companies,” said the report.
India is a quiet corner in the Asia equity universe. Foreign investors have taken out $15 billion from this market since the beginning of the year. The Indian market has underperformed during this period and that might be about to change, it said.
Key challenges
A key reason for this underperformance is a slowdown in earnings while valuations remained elevated. Consumption and investment trends are weak and in response, the administration is focused on boosting consumption and the central bank is easing.
Together with moderate inflation, this can support domestic demand and earnings, said the report.
While growth can help boost consumption in the near term, for a more sustainable pick-up, wages and private capex will have to improve.
Another issue that hangs over Indian earnings is the 50 per cent US tariff on imports from India. Indeed, India faces some of the highest US tariff rates in the world, but most listed equities are domestic in nature and less than 4 per cent of sales for all BSE-500 companies come via exports of goods to the US. When it comes to earnings growth, the direct impact from tariffs is muted. “The growth recovery is likely to be gradual, but we think the risks are reflected in valuations. 2025 consensus forecasts for earnings growth have come down – they are now at 12 per cent and we expect this to drop to 8-9 per cent. For the next year, estimates of 15 per cent might appear high and much will depend on how effective the policies will be in reviving growth,” said the report.
Published on September 24, 2025

Title   : India's Capri Global Capital plans $733 million fundraise in FY26, exec says 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-24T12:53:30
Fetched : 2025-09-24T17:21:38.232584
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/indias-capri-global-capital-plans-733-million-fundraise-in-fy26-exec-says/articleshow/124093040.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The non-banking financial company aims to raise 47 billion rupees in the second half of the fiscal, after raising 18 billion rupees from April to September.
The proceeds will be used to expand the loan book and open 200 branches, Managing Director Rajesh Sharma told Reuters.
Capri Global will also raise around 4 billion rupees through a public issue of bonds, with maturities varying from 18 months to 10 years. The issue will open for subscription next week.
The bonds are rated 'AA' by Infomerics and Acuite Ratings, and Trust Investment Advisors is the lead manger for the issue.
Vinay Surana, Capri Global's head of treasury, said the company plans to raise around 10 billion to 15 billion rupees through bonds in the next six months, and could consider another public issue after assessing the response to the upcoming sale.
($1 = 88.6900 Indian rupees)
