Financial metrics temporarily unavailable (rate limited) - 2025-09-24

Title   : Investment TIPS: Why Ray Dalio prefers inflation-protected govt bonds over zero-sum game equities? 
Source  : economictimes.indiatimes.com
Published: 2025-09-24T10:27:48
Fetched : 2025-09-24T18:34:12.608960
URL     : https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/investment-tips-why-ray-dalio-prefers-inflation-protected-govt-bonds-over-zero-sum-game-equities/articleshow/124089992.cms
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
In his view, for an average middle-class investor, TIPs or Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities are a viable option as they guarantee real returns, and if investors hold them till the time of maturity, the returns will beat inflation.
"As a general rule, I don’t think you should be speculating in the markets because it’s a zero-sum game and you’ll probably lose. That’s why I think TIPS (Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities) are a great option. They guarantee a real return — meaning that if you hold the bond until it matures, your return will exceed the rate of inflation," he tweeted.
As a general rule, I don’t think you should be speculating in the markets because it’s a zero sum game and you’ll probably lose.
— Ray Dalio (@RayDalio) September 22, 2025
That’s why I think TIPS (Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities) are a great option. They guarantee a real return — meaning that if you hold the bond… pic.twitter.com/jYYN9gr4bz
Dalio is the founder of Bridgewater Associates, a premier asset management firm in the US. He has authored several books, including 'Principles', 'The Changing World Order', and 'How Countries Go Broke'.
Dalio has exited Bridgewater Associates, selling his remaining stake in the firm in July. In a letter dated July 21, Bridgewater CEO Nir Bar Dea and Co-Chair Mike McGavick informed clients that the company had repurchased the last remaining ownership shares held by entities related to Dalio.
With $92.1 billion in assets under management, Bridgewater remains the world’s largest hedge fund. Dalio’s complete exit marked the end of an era and the full handoff to a new generation of leaders poised to guide the firm into its next chapter.
However, the legendary fund manager has been warning against the risks facing U.S. government debt, calling it more severe than what Moody’s downgrade reflects, arguing that the real risks of holding American government debt are greater than they appear.
Dalio is one of the few to foresee the 2008 financial crisis. He had said in a post on microblogging site X (formerly Twitter) that credit ratings fail to capture the broader risks to holders of U.S. Treasurys. “You should know that credit ratings understate credit risks because they only rate the risk of the government not paying its debt,” he wrote. “They don’t include the greater risk that the countries in debt will print money to pay their debts, thus causing holders of the bonds to suffer losses from the decreased value of the money they’re getting (rather than from the decreased quantity of money they’re getting).”
“Said differently, for those who care about the value of their money, the risks for U.S. government debt are greater than the rating agencies are conveying,” Dalio added.
Read More: Ray Dalio, who warned of 2008 market crash, says U.S. Treasury risk greater than what Moody’s downgrade suggests
